        "Answer": "The following have been considered as 'compelling reasons' to deprive a mother of custody: a. Neglect; b. Abandonment; c. Unemployment; d. Immorality; (Espiritu v. Court of Appeals, G.R. No. 115640, 15 Mar. 1995) e. Alcoholism; f. Drug addiction; g. Maltreatment; h. Insanity; i. Highly communicable serious disease; j. Grave physical handicap; and k. Serious and credible threat by the child to ham himself if separated from his mother: (Luna v. IAC, G.R. No. L-68374, 18 June 1985)"
