        "Question": "Sara borrowed P50,000.00 from Julia and orally promised to pay it within six months. When Sara tried to pay her debt on the 8th month, Julia demanded the payment of interest of 12% per annum because of Sara's delay in payment. Sara paid her debt and the interest claimed by Julia. After rethinking, Sara demanded back from Julia the amount she had paid as interest. Julia claims she has no obligation to return the interest paid by Sara because it was a natural obligation which Sara voluntarily performed and can no longer recover. Do you agree? Explain.",
        "Answer": "NO. Under the Civil Code, natural obligations are those not based on positive law but on equity and natural law. (Art. 1423, NCC) The obligation in this case is based on positive law, particularly the provisions governing solutio indebiti or payment by mistake. (Art. 22, NCC) Applying the Civil Code, Sara has no demandable obligation to pay interest because no stipulation for the payment of such was made in writing. (Art. 1956, NCC) Thus, there was a payment by mistake made by Sara."
