        "Question": "Distinguish between ex post facto law and bill of attainder. ",
        "Answer": "Ex post facto law is any law which makes an innocent act a crime after the act was committed. It is a Latin phrase which means “from something done afterwards.” It could also be a law which aggravates a crime, or makes it greater than when it was committed, or which changes the punishment and inflicts a greater penalty than the law governing the crime when committed. A bill of attainder is a law which inflicts punishment on a named individual or a group of individuals without judicial trial. Ex post facto law pertains to the act while a bill of attainder pertains to a named individual or to members of a group."
