        "Question": "What are the constitutional provisions limiting the power of Congress to enact penal laws? ",
        "Answer": "The constitutional provisions limiting the power of Congress to enact penal laws are the following: 1. The law must not be an ex post facto law or it should not be given a retroactive effect. 2. The law must not be a bill of attainder, meaning it cannot provide punishment without judicial process. 3. The law must not impose cruel, unusual or degrading punishment. 4. No person shall be held to answer for a criminal offense without due process of law."
