        "Answer": "The judge may appreciate the aggravating circumstance of recidivism. A recidivist is one who, at the time of his trial for one crime, shall have been previously convicted by final judgment of another crime embraced in the same title of the RPC. Robbery, theft, estafa are crimes against property embraced in Title Ten of the RPC. The judge may also appreciate the aggravating circumstance of habituality or reiteracion, because there have been two or more crimes committed for which she has been published, regardless of the degree of penalty."
