        "Question": "Because of the barbarity and the hideousness of the acts committed by the suspects/ respondents in cutting off their victims’ appendages... the Commission on Human Rights (CHR) investigating team recommended to the panel of public prosecutors that all respondents be charged with violation of the Heinous Crimes Law. As the chief prosecutor tasked with approving the filing of the information, how will you pass upon the recommendation? Explain?  (2010 Bar Question)",
        "Answer": "The CHR is correct in describing the crimes committed as “heinous crimes”... despite the passage of Rep. Act No. 9346 prohibiting the imposition of the death penalty. However, the “Heinous Crimes Law” does not define crimes; it is only an amendatory law increasing the penalty for the crimes specified therein as heinous, to a maximum of death. Thus, the heinous crimes committed shall be prosecuted under the penal law they are respectively defined and penalized... The crime shall be designated as defined and punished under the penal law violated and the penalty shall be reclusion perpetua without the benefit of parole or life imprisonment without the benefit of parole, as the case maybe in lieu of the death penalty."
