        "subject": "Criminal Law",
        "No": 200,
        "Question": "A postal van containing mail matters, including checks and treasury warrants, was hijacked along a national highway by ten (10) men, two (2) of whom were armed. They used force, violence and intimidation against three (3) postal employees who were occupants of the van, resulting in the unlawful taking and transportation of the entire van and its contents. If you were the public prosecutor, would you charge the ten (10) men who hijacked the postal van with violation of Presidential Decree No. 532, otherwise known as the Anti-Piracy and Anti -Highway Robbery Law of 1974? Explain your answer. ",
        "Answer": "Yes. The ten (10) men who hijacked the postal van should be charged with highway robbery, which is punished under P.D. 532. All the elements of highway robbery are present: (1) there is unlawful taking of personal property belonging to another (the mail van and its contents); (2) the taking is by means of violence against or intimidation of person or force upon things (used force, violence, and intimidation against the postal employees who were occupants of the van); (3) the commission is committed on any Philippine highway (along a national highway); and (4) the perpetrators are highway robbers or brigands (at least 4 armed persons commit the crime)."
