        "subject": "Criminal Law",
        "No": 295,
        "Question": "Charlie was charged for the qualified rape of AAA... AAA was 14 years old... and Charlie was AAA's stepfather... BBB (AAA's mother) and Charlie only became live-in partners after CCC's (AAA's father) death. The RTC found Charlie guilty of qualified rape. On appeal, the Court of Appeals convicted Charlie of simple rape. Charlie appealed before the Supreme Court. How will you rule and why? ",
        "Answer": "I will rule that Charlie is guilty of qualified rape. Rape is qualified when the offender is the step-father of the victim (Art. 266-B). It is settled that in rape, the relationship of step-father and step-daughter is included in the concept of a ‘legal relationship of relationship by affinity’ (People v. Abaro, G.R. No. 105598, March 14, 1995)... The legal tie of affinity between the parties is not affected by the subsequent dissolution of the marriage or by the death of the spouse."
