        "subject": "Criminal Law",
        "No": 383,
        "Question": "In her weekly gossip column in a tabloid, Gigi wrote an unflattering article about Pablo, a famous singer, and his bitter separation from his wife... Pablo charged Gigi with libel. In her defense, Gigi countered that she did not commit libel because Pablo has attained the status of a public figure so that even his personal life has become a legitimate subject of public interest and comment. Is Gigi correct?  (A) Yes, because Pablo’s private life has become a public interest. (B) No, because Pablo's private life, even if he is a celebrity, is not a subject of privileged communication. (C) No, Gigi must have been motivated by actual malice to be liable. (D) Yes, but Gigi must show that the imputation is true and made with good motives and for justifiable ends.",
