        "Question": "The management and Union X in Atisan Mining entered into a CBA for 1997 to 2001. After 6 months, a majority of the members of Union X formed Union Y and sought management recognition. The latter responded by not dealing with either union. But, when the CBA’s economic provisions had to be renegotiated towards the end of the term of the CBA, the management chose to negotiate with Union Y, the newer union. Thus, Union X which negotiated the existing CBA charged the company with unfair labor practice (ULP). The company argued that it committed no unfair labor practice since the supposed violation had nothing to do with economic provisions of the CBA. Is the management right? (2011 BAR)",
        "Answer": "No. The duty to bargain collectively is not merely confined to economic provisions but to all terms and conditions of employment. The management should negotiate with Union X, the existing certified bargaining agent, especially on the economic provisions of the existing CBA because Article 253 of the Labor Code mandates the continuance of the terms and conditions in the CBA until a new one is executed."
