        "Answer": "A strike may be an economic strike, namely, it is a strike caused by a deadlock at the bargaining table. A deadlock may arise because the offer of the employer, e.g., its offer of a 20% across-the-board increase in wages and salaries, was not accepted by the Union who wanted a 50% increase. After considering the matter, the employer may improve its offer, e.g. it offers a 35% increase. This improved offer of the employer may be submitted to the union members on or before the 30th day of the strike. The secret balloting that will determine whether a majority of the union members accept the improved offer of the employer is the so-called ''improved offer balloting. In case it is a lockout, and not a strike, what may be the subject matter of a secret balloting, this lime among the members of the Board of Directors of the employer, may be the reduced offer of the union, i.e., instead of asking for 50% across the board increase in wages and salaries, it may reduce its demand to 25 % ."
