        "Answer": "The non-stock, non-profit hospital’s income from paying patients is subject to a preferential income tax of 10%. In Commissioner of Internal Revenue v. St. Luke’s Medical Center, the Supreme Court laid down the rules on the treatment of iconic tax of non-profit hospitals. Pursuant to Sec. 30(E) and (G) of the NIRC, these hospitals are exempt from income tax with respect to their activities conducted exclusively for charitable or social welfare purposes. However, they are subject to a preferential income tax rate of 10% under charitable or social welfare purposes."
